## Instruction

You are preparing a graduate application report for a student who wants to apply for a top computer science master program in the United States in 2025 and start in 2026. Please help me find the detailed language requirements for all the American universities ranked in the **worldwide top ten** in the 2025 QS World University Rankings in the field of computer science. For each eligible university, please collect the following information: 1) University name, city and QS computer science ranking; (Please fulfill the names based on the QS ranking. Please save the information as "cs_top10_us_2025.xlsx" file, strictly following the headers in `format.xlsx` without any change. <figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><img fetchpriority="high" decoding="async" width="1024" height="683" src="https://www.eecs.mit.edu/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/MSRP-Robotics-Lab-tour-3-cropped-1024x683.jpeg" alt="" class="wp-image-3280" srcset="https://www.eecs.mit.edu/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/MSRP-Robotics-Lab-tour-3-cropped-1024x683.jpeg 1024w, https://www.eecs.mit.edu/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/MSRP-Robotics-Lab-tour-3-cropped-750x500.jpeg 750w, https://www.eecs.mit.edu/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/MSRP-Robotics-Lab-tour-3-cropped-225x150.jpeg 225w, https://www.eecs.mit.edu/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/MSRP-Robotics-Lab-tour-3-cropped-768x512.jpeg 768w, https://www.eecs.mit.edu/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/MSRP-Robotics-Lab-tour-3-cropped-1536x1024.jpeg 1536w, https://www.eecs.mit.edu/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/MSRP-Robotics-Lab-tour-3-cropped-2048x1365.jpeg 2048w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">Students tour a robotics lab in this photo taken by Pedro Colon Hernandez. </figcaption></figure>



<p>The EECS Department is the largest in the School of Engineering with about 700 graduate students in the doctoral program. [Application is for the doctoral program only â€” there is no terminal masters degree, but all PhD students earn a masters degree as they work towards PhD. &nbsp;A Masters of Engineering is only available for qualified MIT EECS undergraduates.]&nbsp;</p>



<p>The application website (see link below) is available on September 15, 2025, for students who wish to apply for graduate admission in September 2026. The deadline for submitting completed applications is December 1, 2025.</p>



<p>Applicants to the MIT EECS graduate program should apply using the<a href="https://gradapply.mit.edu/eecs">&nbsp;<strong>EECS online admissions site</strong></a>.&nbsp;</p>



<p>Admissions decisions will be sent by the Office of Graduate Education using a new MIT Application Management system.</p>



<p>Questions not answered by the&nbsp;<strong><a href="https://www.eecs.mit.edu/academics/graduate-programs/admission-process/graduate-admissions-faqs/" data-type="URL" data-id="https://www.eecs.mit.edu/academics/graduate-programs/admission-process/graduate-admissions-faqs/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">FAQs</a></strong>? Please send inquiries not already addressed by the previous link to&nbsp;<strong><a href="mailto:grad-ap@eecs.mit.edu">grad-ap@eecs.mit.edu</a></strong>. Any inquiries regarding the MIT Application Management platform should be sent to <a href="mailto:gradadmissions@mit.edu">gradadmissions@mit.edu</a>.</p>



<p>Questions about general MIT Graduate Admissions? Please see the Office of Graduate Education&#8217;s <a href="https://oge.mit.edu/graduate-admissions/frequently-asked-questions/">Frequently Asked Questions</a>.</p>



<p>For information on our faculty and what they&#8217;re currently working on, take a look at our <a href="https://eecsis.mit.edu/research_interests.pcgi" data-type="link" data-id="https://eecsis.mit.edu/research_interests.pcgi">Faculty Interests Guide.</a></p>



<p>For more information about answering the essay questions, see <a href="https://mitcommlab.mit.edu/eecs/commkit/graduate-school-personal-statement/">this article from the MIT EECS Communication Lab</a>.</p>

field--label-hidden field__item\"><p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Click <a href=\"/university-rankings-articles/university-subject-rankings/top-universities-us-computer-science-2018\">here</a> to read an updated version of this article, based on the QS World University Rankings by Subject 2018.</strong></p>\n<p>Are you thinking of studying <a href=\"/courses/computer-science-information-systems/guide\">computer science</a> in the <a href=\"/student-info/qs-guides/how-to-study-abroad-in-the-US\">United States</a>? The country has a strong presence in the <a href=\"/university-rankings/university-subject-rankings/2016/computer-science-information-systems\">computer science ranking</a> in the latest edition of the <a href=\"/subject-rankings\">QS World University Rankings by Subject</a>, boasting an impressive 90 entries out of the 500 featured. Read on for an overview of the <strong>top 10 universities in the US for computer science</strong>, plus other high-ranking US institutions in this field.</p>\n<h2>1.Â <a href=\"/universities/massachusetts-institute-technology-mit/\">Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT)</a></h2>\n<p></p>\n<p>Frequently found at the top of the subject rankings tables, the <strong>Massachusetts Institute of Technology</strong> (MIT) is ranked 1<sup>st</sup> for computer science and has also been the worldâ€™s leading university in the overall <a title=\"View the 2016 rankings here\" href=\"/university-rankings/world-university-rankings/2016\">QS World University RankingsÂ®</a> for five consecutive years. MITâ€™s computer science department, combined with <a href=\"/courses/engineering-electrical-electronic/guide\">electrical engineering</a>, is the largest department at the institution. The university is well-known for its innovative research in this area, with its computer science faculty and researchers having made fundamental contributions to cybernetics, artificial intelligence, computer languages, machine learning, robotics, and cryptography.</p>\n<h2>2.Â <a href=\"/universities/stanford-university/\">Stanford University</a></h2>\n<p></p>\n<p>Ranked 2<sup>nd</sup> both for computer science and in the overall World University Rankings this year, <strong>Stanford University</strong>â€™s setting near the famous SiliconÂ  Valley in <a href=\"/where-to-study/north-america/united-states/california/study-california\">California</a> makes it unique amongst these top universities in the US, with many of the worldâ€™s largest high-tech corporations right on its doorstep. Stanfordâ€™s computer science department was founded in 1965 and is part of the universityâ€™s School of Engineering.</p>\n<h2>3. <a href=\"/universities/harvard-university/\">Harvard University</a></h2>\n<p></p>\n<p><strong>Harvard University</strong> is ranked 4<sup>th</sup> in the world in the latest computer science ranking. Its computer science department is part of the John A. Paulson School of Engineering and Applied Sciences (founded in 1847, with computer science courses available from 1984). Famous technology magnates to have studied at Harvard include Microsoft founder Bill Gates and Facebook founder Mark Zuckerburg (both of whom famously â€˜dropped outâ€™ to pursue their careers in tech).</p>\n<h2>4.Â <a href=\"/universities/carnegie-mellon-university\">Carnegie Mellon University</a></h2>\n<p></p>\n<p>The next of the top universities in the US for computer science is <strong>Carnegie Mellon University</strong>, based in the city of <a href=\"/university-rankings-articles/qs-best-student-cities/pittsburgh\">Pittsburgh</a>, Pennsylvania. Within the QS World University Rankings by Subject, Carnegie Mellon University achieves its strongest score in the field of computer science, ranked 5<sup>th</sup> in the world in this field. Its School of Computer Science is based at the Gates and Hillman Centers, a US$98 million complex which opened in 2009 and has achieved LEED Gold certification for its high levels of sustainability.</p>\n<h2>5.Â <a href=\"/universities/university-california-berkeley-ucb\">University of California, Berkeley (UCB)</a></h2>\n<p></p>\n<p>The <strong>University of California, Berkeley</strong> is ranked 7<sup>th</sup> in the world for computer science this year, and like MIT combines its computer science school with electrical engineering. The Turing Award, known as the â€˜Nobel Prize in computingâ€™ has been awarded to 11 alumni and 10 past and present faculty members of Berkeley, including Douglas Engelbart, the inventor of the computer mouse.</p>\n<h2>6.Â <a href=\"/universities/princeton-university\">Princeton University</a></h2>\n<p></p>\n<p>Ranked 10<sup>th</sup> in the world for computer science, <strong>Princeton University</strong>â€™s computer science department is part of the universityâ€™s School of Engineering and Applied Science, in which 1,900 students are enrolled. Its alumni include â€˜father of computer scienceâ€™ Alan Turing, computer scientists Alonzo Church and John von Neumann, and Amazon CEO and founder Jeff Bezos.</p>\n<h2>7.Â <a href=\"/universities/university-california-los-angeles-ucla\">University of California, Los Angeles (UCLA)</a></h2>\n<p></p>\n<p>TheÂ <strong>University of California, Los Angeles</strong>Â (UCLA) is ranked 16<sup>th</sup> in the world for computer science this year. Its computer science faculty is part of the UCLA Henry Samueli School of Engineering and Applied Science, which is credited as being â€˜the birthplace of the internetâ€™, as the first transmission of what would become the internet was sent from the universityâ€™s Boelter Hall in 1969.</p>\n<h2>8.Â <a href=\"/universities/georgia-institute-technology\">Georgia Institute of Technology (Georgia Tech)</a></h2>\n<p></p>\n<p>The next of the top universities in the US for computer science is <strong>Georgia Institute of Technology </strong>(Georgia Tech), up 14 places this year to rank 25<sup>th</sup> for computer science. Its College of Computing has about 4,570 students enrolled on 18 degree programs and is located at the Klaus Advanced Computing Building (KACB), a LEED Gold certified building with six research centers and 70 research laboratories.</p>\n<h2>9.Â <a href=\"/universities/cornell-university\">Cornell University</a></h2>\n<p></p>\n<p>Heading to the state of <a href=\"/where-to-study/north-america/united-states/new-york/study-new-york\">New York</a>, <strong>Cornell University</strong> is currently ranked joint 26<sup>th</sup> in the world for computer science, sharing this spot with Canadaâ€™s University of Waterloo. Its department of computer science was established in 1965, making it one of the oldest of its kind in the country. Based in Ithaca, the university runs a technology-focused graduate campus in <a href=\"/university-rankings-articles/qs-best-student-cities/new-york\">New York City</a>, known as Cornell Tech.</p>\n<h2>=10. <a href=\"/universities/california-institute-technology-caltech\">California Institute of Technology (Caltech)</a></h2>\n<p></p>\n<p>Sharing 28<sup>th</sup> place in the world for computer science this year, <strong>California Institute of Technology</strong> is known as one of the <a href=\"/student-info/choosing-university/mit-or-caltech\">USâ€™s top tech schools</a>, with a noted alumni of scientific researchers, astronauts and business founders, including Sabeer Bhatia (founder of Hotmail). Like the university itself, the Computing and Mathematical Sciences Faculty is small, with only 20 faculty members and 150 students.</p>\n<h2>=10. <a href=\"/universities/university-washington\">University of Washington</a></h2>\n<p></p>\n<p>Joining Caltech at joint 28<sup>th</sup> in the world for computer science, the <strong>University of Washingtonâ€™s</strong> college of computer science and engineering was established as an inter-college graduate program in 1967. Undergraduates often participate in research, with 33 students at the university winning the Computing Research Association Undergraduate Research Award over a decade, more than any other program in the nation.</p>\n<h2>Other top universities in the US for computer science</h2>\n<p>Many more top universities in the US are included in the computer science ranking, including the <a href=\"/universities/university-illinois-urbana-champaign\">University of Illinois at Urbanaâ€“Champaign</a> (30<sup>th</sup>), <a href=\"/universities/columbia-university\">Columbia University</a> (joint 31<sup>st</sup>) and the <a href=\"/universities/university-texas-austin\">University of Texas at Austin</a> (34<sup>th</sup>). Six more US universities feature in the global top 50 for computer science, and eight more in the top 100. class=\"eecs-accordion\">\n\t\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<h3 class=\"eecs-panel-title\"><span id=\"faq-1\" class=\"eecs-accord-link\">1. Who is eligible to apply to EECS? </span></h3>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<div class=\"eecs-panel-content\"><p>We expect applicants to have earned a Bachelor&#8217;s degree by the time they register in EECS, and to possess a very strong background in math, physics, computer science, or engineering. Admission is extremely competitive.</p>\n</div>\n\t\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<h3 class=\"eecs-panel-title\"><span id=\"faq-2\" class=\"eecs-accord-link\">2. How do I apply?</span></h3>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<div class=\"eecs-panel-content\"><p>To apply to our graduate application, you must use the EECS departmental admissions application which is available at: <a href=\"https://gradapply.mit.edu/eecs\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">https://gradapply.mit.edu/eecs</a>. A few sections of the application are editable after submission, including the &#8220;Research Activities and Goals&#8221; and &#8220;Academic and Intellectual Journey&#8221; essays.</p>\n<p>We request that all letters of recommendation be uploaded electronically to the GradApply application by your recommenders. Copies of transcripts are uploaded to the application. Admitted students will be required to submit official transcripts to the EECS Graduate Office via regular or express mail delivery. Please do not send any documents other than your official transcript(s). The mailing address for this is:</p>\n<p>EECS Graduate Office, Room 38-444, MIT, 77 Massachusetts Avenue, Cambridge, MA 02139. Since we use express couriers such as FedEx and DHL for notifying admitted applicants, please try to avoid using PO boxes in your mailing address.</p>\n<p>Once your application has been received when submitted to Grad Apply, you will be prompted to create a second account on an admissions decision notification platform â€œMIT Application Managementâ€. All decisions related to your submitted application will be posted in â€œMIT Application Managementâ€. Questions regarding the MIT Application Management system may be directed to the Office of Graduate Education (OGE) atÂ <a href=\"mailto:gradadmissions@mit.edu\">gradadmissions@mit.edu</a>â€‹.</p>\n</div>\n\t\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<h3 class=\"eecs-panel-title\"><span id=\"faq-3\" class=\"eecs-accord-link\">3. Is the deadline the same for the application and supporting documents?</span></h3>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<div class=\"eecs-panel-content\"><p>No, the deadline for submitting your application is December 1 and the <strong>online application system</strong> will shut down that day. However, the online letter system will stay open for several more weeks. Your letters and transcripts should be uploaded to the online application by early January. Review of the application will include review of credentials posted to the application at the time of that review.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>In addition, we will continue to accept IELTS/TOEFL Test results after the deadline.Â  The IELTS/TOEFL check will be the final check of the decision. If the Admission Committee has a question regarding the TOEFL/IELTS scores, you will be contacted.</p>\n</div>\n\t\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<h3 class=\"eecs-panel-title\"><span id=\"faq-4\" class=\"eecs-accord-link\">4. How do I pay for the application fee?</span></h3>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<div class=\"eecs-panel-content\"><p>The online system requires you to pay with a credit card. (Applicants should avoid using PO boxes in their return addresses).</p>\n</div>\n\t\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<h3 class=\"eecs-panel-title\"><span id=\"faq-5\" class=\"eecs-accord-link\">5. I applied earlier; how may I reapply?</span></h3>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<div class=\"eecs-panel-content\"><p>You should fill out a completely new online application. You may indicate that you applied earlier by checking the appropriate box.</p>\n</div>\n\t\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<h3 class=\"eecs-panel-title\"><span id=\"faq-6\" class=\"eecs-accord-link\">6. What documents are necessary for applying to EECS?</span></h3>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<div class=\"eecs-panel-content\"><p>The application consists of four parts: The biographical section, three (3) letters of recommendation, â€œRecord of Subjectsâ€ with grades, and two essays, one about your Research Activities and Goals, and the other about your Academic and Intellectual Journey. For more information about writing a statement of objectives, see<a href=\"https://mitcommlab.mit.edu/eecs/commkit/graduate-school-personal-statement/\"> this article from the MIT EECS Communication Lab</a>.</p>\n</div>\n\t\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<h3 class=\"eecs-panel-title\"><span id=\"faq-7\" class=\"eecs-accord-link\">7. I am an MIT undergraduate in EECS. Should I fill out the â€œRecord of Subjectsâ€?</span></h3>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<div class=\"eecs-panel-content\"><p>Yes, you should list all subjects and grades that do not appear on your uploaded transcript. With the new online procedure for evaluating applications, it is necessary for us to view all the grades online if they do not appear on your transcript. All admitted students will be required to send official transcripts to the EECS Graduate Office, Room 38-444.</p>\n</div>\n\t\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<h3 class=\"eecs-panel-title\"><span id=\"faq-8\" class=\"eecs-accord-link\">8. Should I list the subjects that I am currently taking on the â€œRecord of Subjectsâ€?</span></h3>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<div class=\"eecs-panel-content\"><p>You should list all subjects that do not appear on your transcripts.</p>\n</div>\n\t\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<h3 class=\"eecs-panel-title\"><span id=\"faq-9\" class=\"eecs-accord-link\">9.             <div class="su-wysiwyg-text paragraph stanford-wysiwyg text-long label-hidden"><h2>Overview</h2><p><span>Completed online applications must be submitted by the </span><a href="https://csd9.sites.stanford.edu/admissions-graduate-application-deadlines"><span>CS application deadlines</span></a><span>. The online application can be found&nbsp;</span><a href="https://gradadmissions.stanford.edu/applying"><span>here</span></a><span>.</span></p><p><span>Please note that we are not able to reactivate applications or supporting documents from previous applications. If you're reapplying, you must follow the same application requirements as new applicants by submitting a new online application and new supporting documents.</span></p><h3>PhD and MS Application Checklist</h3><ul><li><strong>Application fee</strong>. The application fee of $125 is to be paid in the online application with a credit card.</li><li><strong>Statement of purpose</strong>. Your statement of purpose should be concise, focused, and well written. It should describe succinctly your reasons for applying to the proposed program at Stanford, your preparation for this field of study, research interests, future career plans, and other aspects of your background and interests which may aid the admissions committee in evaluating your aptitude and motivation for graduate study. The statement of purpose must be no more than two pages in length, single-spaced. It will be submitted as part of the online application.</li><li><strong>3 recommendation letters</strong>. In the online application, you will be asked to identify your recommenders and their email addresses. Please notify your recommenders that they will receive an email prompt to submit their recommendation online. CS only accepts online recommendations through the application system. CS cannot accept mailed, emailed, or faxed recommendations.<ul><li>You must submit a minimum/maximum of three recommendation letters and they must be submitted through the online application system. &nbsp;</li><li>We recommend that at least two of these letters be from academic sources. Please have your recommender write candidly about your qualifications, potential to carry on advanced study in the field specified, intellectual independence, capacity for analytical thinking, ability to organize and express ideas clearly, and potential for teaching. In describing such attributes as motivation, intellect, and maturity, specific examples are more useful than generalizations.</li><li>We do not consider letters of recommendations submitted via Interfolio.</li><li>For more information on submitting letters of recommendation visit <a href="https://gradadmissions.stanford.edu/applying/starting-your-application/submitting-online-recommendations">here</a>.</li></ul></li><li><strong>Resume</strong>. Submit your resume in the online application and include any publications.</li><li><strong>Supplemental form</strong>. This form is part of the online application. List any publications and your website on this form and on your resume (CV). Upload your resume (CV) on the document uploads, confirmation and submission section (page 15). Additionally, attach a copy of your NDO transcript on the additional information's section of the online application.</li><li><strong>Transcripts</strong>. You are required to upload unofficial copies of your transcripts or e-transcripts onto the online application for all institutions you have attended for at least a year as a full time student.             <div class="su-wysiwyg-text paragraph stanford-wysiwyg text-long label-hidden"><h2>Overview</h2><p><span>Completed online applications must be submitted by the </span><a href="https://csd9.sites.stanford.edu/admissions-graduate-application-deadlines"><span>CS application deadlines</span></a><span>. The online application can be found&nbsp;</span><a href="https://gradadmissions.stanford.edu/applying"><span>here</span></a><span>.</span></p><p><span>Please note that we are not able to reactivate applications or supporting documents from previous applications. If you're reapplying, you must follow the same application requirements as new applicants by submitting a new online application and new supporting documents.</span></p><h3>PhD and MS Application Checklist</h3><ul><li><strong>Application fee</strong>. The application fee of $125 is to be paid in the online application with a credit card.</li><li><strong>Statement of purpose</strong>. Your statement of purpose should be concise, focused, and well written. It should describe succinctly your reasons for applying to the proposed program at Stanford, your preparation for this field of study, research interests, future career plans, and other aspects of your background and interests which may aid the admissions committee in evaluating your aptitude and motivation for graduate study. The statement of purpose must be no more than two pages in length, single-spaced. It will be submitted as part of the online application.</li><li><strong>3 recommendation letters</strong>. In the online application, you will be asked to identify your recommenders and their email addresses. Please notify your recommenders that they will receive an email prompt to submit their recommendation online. CS only accepts online recommendations through the application system. CS cannot accept mailed, emailed, or faxed recommendations.<ul><li>You must submit a minimum/maximum of three recommendation letters and they must be submitted through the online application system. &nbsp;</li><li>We recommend that at least two of these letters be from academic sources. Please have your recommender write candidly about your qualifications, potential to carry on advanced study in the field specified, intellectual independence, capacity for analytical thinking, ability to organize and express ideas clearly, and potential for teaching. In describing such attributes as motivation, intellect, and maturity, specific examples are more useful than generalizations.</li><li>We do not consider letters of recommendations submitted via Interfolio.</li><li>For more information on submitting letters of recommendation visit <a href="https://gradadmissions.stanford.edu/applying/starting-your-application/submitting-online-recommendations">here</a>.</li></ul></li><li><strong>Resume</strong>. Submit your resume in the online application and include any publications.</li><li><strong>Supplemental form</strong>. This form is part of the online application. List any publications and your website on this form and on your resume (CV). Upload your resume (CV) on the document uploads, confirmation and submission section (page 15). Additionally, attach a copy of your NDO transcript on the additional information's section of the online application.</li><li><strong>Transcripts</strong>. You are required to upload unofficial copies of your transcripts or e-transcripts onto the online application for all institutions you have attended for at least a year as a full time student. Transcripts from Stanford's <a href="https://csd9.sites.stanford.edu/admissions/non-degree-option">Non-Degree Option (NDO)</a> program should also be uploaded. Do not mail your official transcripts unless we contact you to do so. For more information on the minimum level of study required of applicants who wish to apply for graduate study at Stanford, please visit <a href="https://gradadmissions.stanford.edu/applying/international-applicants">here</a>.</li><li><strong>GRE</strong>. These are not required for PhD or MS applicants.</li><li><p><strong>TOEFL/IELTS</strong>. Stanford University accepts <a href="https://gradadmissions.stanford.edu/apply/test-scores#toefl">TOEFL scores</a> to prove English proficiency. The <a href="http://www.toefl.org/">TOEFL</a> test may be taken no earlier than 24 months (two years) prior to the application deadline. Be sure to take the test in time for your scores to be received at Stanford by the application deadline. <strong>Stanford Institution code: 4704</strong> (no department code is required).</p><p>We also accept IELTS Academic scores as an equivalent substitute for TOEFL scores.&nbsp;To learn more about interpreting IELTS scores, refer to the following resources:&nbsp;<a href="https://ielts.org/organisations/ielts-for-organisations/get-started-with-ielts/setting-ielts-entry-scores#Score-overview">IELTS Scoring Scale</a>&nbsp;|&nbsp;<a href="https://ielts.org/organisations/ielts-for-organisations/compare-ielts">IELTS/TOEFL Score Equivalency Table</a>&nbsp;|&nbsp;<a href="https://ielts.org/researchers/our-research/research-reports/score-concordance-study-between-ielts-academic-and-toefl-ibt">IELTS/TOEFL Comparison Report</a>. The IELTS test may be taken no earlier than 24 months (two years) prior to the application deadline. If you are submitting IELTS scores to satisfy Stanfordâ€™s English proficiency test requirement, you must report your official scores directly to Stanford via the IELTS Results Service E-delivery option. Our organizationâ€™s account name is&nbsp;<strong>Stanford University Graduate.&nbsp;</strong></p><ul><li><p><strong>English proficiency test scores are not required for:</strong></p><ul><li>U.S. citizens and permanent residents.</li><li>Applicants who self-declare their first language is English.</li><li>Applicants who earned a U.S. bachelorâ€™s, masterâ€™s or doctoral degree, or international equivalent from a university where all instruction was conducted in English.</li><li>Applicants with two or more consecutive years of professional or educational experience in English, in the past 10 years.</li></ul><p>For information on <strong>the university's minimum TOEFL/IELTS score for admission consideration</strong>, visit <a href="https://gradadmissions.stanford.edu/apply/test-scores#toefl">Test Scores.</a>&nbsp;</p></li></ul></li></ul><p><strong>IMPORTANT NOTE</strong>: Do <strong>not</strong> mail any other paper documents to the admissions office such as publications, or financial statements/documents, as they will not be reviewed by the admissions committee. We will not upload documents to your applicant file if they are emailed to us.</p><h3>Coterm Application Checklist</h3><ul><li><strong>CS Coterm application form</strong>. Your statement of purpose should be concise, focused, and well written. It should describe succinctly your reasons for applying to the proposed program at Stanford.</li></ul></li><li><strong>Three letters of recommendation</strong>. In the online application, you will be asked to identify your recommenders and their email addresses. Notify your recommenders that they will receive an email prompt to submit their recommendations online.<ul><li>You must submit a minimum/maximum of three recommendation letters and they must be submitted through the online application system. At least two of these letters should be from academic sources. Have your recommender write candidly about your qualifications, potential to carry on advanced study in the field specified, intellectual independence, capacity for analytical thinking, ability to organize and express ideas clearly, and potential for teaching. In describing such attributes as motivation, intellect, and maturity, specific examples are more useful than generalizations.</li></ul></li><li><strong>Transcripts</strong>.
